text: I watch your python tutorials quite a bit and came across this vid due to the S2000 pic. What track is that? I have a few vids of Roebling, Sebring, and the FIRM on my channel. Was on s2ki as nissanfanatic for a few years until I sold mine.  Also, I found quite a bit of differential pressure approximately 16.5" back from the front of the hood using a manometer (Thats how I decided where to place my hood vent). It measured right around 0.06lb/in^2 at 60mph, which is the maximum dynamic pressure of air. I also ran distilled water + 1 bottle of Motul MoCool (surfactant) and I noticed about a six degree drop on average after a few laps.

author: @tsukikage
text: Just watched all your Q&A videos to make sure this question wasn't already answered. Long story short, I've explored many different fields (math, linguistics, computer science, accounting, etc.) to try to find something that I actually felt confident enough in to pursue as a career, and in all of these fields I did very well at the *very* beginning, but once I moved on to meatier material I felt that I either didn't have the problem solving skills or the efficiency compared to my peers to actually succeed in that field. An assignment that was supposed to take me 5-10 hours would take me 20.  My question is this: do you have any recommendations for finding out in the earlier stages of learning to program if you actually have the proper intellect it takes to make a career out of it?  One other question: I'm somewhat of a beginner to both Python and programming, and one of my goals is to start developing useful apps (not games) for Android (and perhaps also iOS). I know it's possible to develop Android apps using Python, but do you happen to know of any good resources for people who are completely new to developing apps (or really anything with a GUI)?
